dc:title: Relative unpalatability of leaf beetles with either biosynthesized or sequestered chemical defence
dc:creator: Rowell-Rahier M.
dc:description: Defence of leaf beetles in the genus Oreina (Chrysomelidae, Coleoptera) is chemically diverse. Some (eg O. gloriosa) rely on the secretion of small quantities of a concentrated mixture of cardenolides that are biosynthesized de novo and stored only in special glands. Others (eg O. cacaliae) lack cardenolides but sequester pyrrolizidine alkaloid N-oxides (PAs) and store them both in their body and in their glands. The impact of the defensive secretions on the palatability of the beetles to red-winged blackbirds Agelaius phoeniceus was tested. Oreina gloriosa, with their secretion of cardenolides intact, were eaten in 55% of trials. When the secretion was physically removed, 95% of O. gloriosa were eaten. The mean handling time by the birds also decreased from 41 to 26s. The small quantity of highly concentrated secretion produced on the surface of the beetle's body thus affords substantial protection against avian predators. Oreina cacaliae, with PAs in their secretion and in their body, were eaten in only 21% of the cases. When the secretion was removed, leaving PA only in the body, the number eaten rose to 36%. Time to peck and then reject the beetles with their secretions intact was less in O. cacaliae than in O. gloriosa. PAs therefore seem to provide the beetle with better protection from the birds than do cardenolides. -from Authors
